snippet.textDisplay:
I actually laughed aloud to myself at #5. Honestly, I like K-pop, or at least the few K-pop groups that I've heard, but... God, I can't think of many groups more obsessive and obnoxious than K-pop stans... (and yes, I know it's super laughable for a brony to be saying that.) So I guess I feel your pain there. BTS is honestly pretty good, it's just the fans who are terrible, and I really hope that BTS entering the Western charts at the very least drowns out the really shitty and disturbing side of their fanbase.


As for Bad Guy... It's alright. I honestly find myself liking a metal cover of it by Ankor more than the original song (look it up if you're into metal, it's pretty great).

snippet.textDisplay:
The "duh" in Bad Guy used to be my least favorite part of the song, but now I think it's brilliant.


She mournfully concludes that she's the bad guy, and it sounds like she's about to sing about how no one knows what it's like to be the bad guy, to be the sad guy behind blue eyes. And that if you looked closer, you'd see a sad misunderstood soul in need of love. That's what you're supposed to say in a song like this, right?


Instead, she says: Duh. I AM the bad guy. Deal with it.

snippet.textDisplay:
SPOILERS:

10. I'm sorry, but I actually really liked Panic! At the Disco's sellout. Sure Brendan Urie's appearance on ME! was a step in the wrong direction, but it's a step towards getting pop music out of that state of misery it was in. I personally like High Hopes more, but I understand the hate.

9. My favorite hit song of the year. We will never have another Old Town Road. Such a legendary phenomenon.

8. I just found this song boring. Maybe I'm just dismissing Ty Dolla $ign. My favorite female rap song this year was "Act Up" by The City Girls for having the greatest opening line ever.

7. Possibly the best hit rap song of the year. Just didn't hear much that hit as deep as 21 showing some true passion. Without J Cole's verse, it'd be my favorite rap hit if the year.

6. I try to enjoy Post Malone, but I just can't fully love him. I can acknowledge that this is a good hit song, but I'll usually check the other pop station to make sure Don't Start Now isn't playing.

5. Haven't gotten into K-Pop, this is probably my favorite K-Pop song I've heard that takes itself seriously. It's a fun song, not too much else I can truly enjoy.

4. I found this song extremely overrated. How exactly are you supposed to feel this. Going back to Don't Start Now, it's a way better song with that topic due to the production you can actually dance to. My opinion on Sam Smith is much different from most people's, I found their 2014-2015 hits much stronger than their more recent work.

3. I'll be frank, this song is good for both Katy Perry AND popular EDM to go out on. I am tired of Pop EDM, it's all the same, except for The Chainsmokers who sound terrible. The only producer I've consistently liked is Calvin Harris and he can't hit here anymore for whatever reason.

2. DaBaby has grown so much on me throughout the year. He is one guy I expect to stick around, could possibly be as big as Drake was last decade. Okay maybe that's a bit much, but he's great and this song is just one of the many I've enjoyed.

HM1. Not a fan.
HM2. Very relaxing, but I can only enjoy it so much.
HM(Money). Nah this was trash.
HM(Shallow). Good song.
HM5. Carly Rae continues to be great.
HM6. Not a fan.
HM7. Haven't listened to this song, but it seems very ambitious so I'll check it out.
HM8. Lizzo's one I can't truly enjoy, but objectively she's great. Juice was very well produced.

1. Out of all the Billie hits. Seriously???? So many better Billie songs than this. The Bieber remix solidified the fact that it wasn't good imo. Side note: you got the point of "Sweet but Psycho" wrong. She hyperbolized her lines and was trying to show that her craziness had a bright side to it. Also that song is way better produced than bad guy, don't @ me.

snippet.textDisplay: What's interesting about Bad Guy (yea spoilers) is that it could both about being like that rebel cool kid that's "bad", and maybe mock the idea of it, or about being bad as in unable to do things right (you can never say "I only good at being bad" on a cool positive tone). It may be the song of edgy teens, but it's also self aware of how silly it is, but still have that uncanny valley of "is she for real?", that's very interesting.
